title: Rangers take lead on bizarre play in Game 5 of ALDS
text:
Frank Gunn Rangers take lead on bizarre play in Game 5 of ALDS 
Home plate umpire Dale Scott, left, signals for Texas Rangers' Rougned Odor to score after conferring with the base umpires to confirm an error by Toronto Blue Jays catcher Russell Martin (not shown) on the play during the seventh inning in Game 5 of baseball's American League Division Series, Wednesday, Oct. 14, 2015 in Toronto. (Frank Gunn/The Canadian Press via AP) MANDATORY CREDIT Nathan Denette Rangers take lead on bizarre play in Game 5 of ALDS 
Toronto Blue Jays manager John Gibbons argues with the umpires after a call during the seventh inning in Game 5 of baseball's American League Division Series against the Texas Rangers, Wednesday, Oct. 14, 2015 in Toronto. (Nathan Denette/The Canadian Press via AP) MANDATORY CREDIT Frank Gunn Rangers take lead on bizarre play in Game 5 of ALDS 
Texas Rangers' Rougned Odor celebrates with teammates after scoring on an error Toronto Blue Jays catcher Russell Martin (not shown) during the seventh inning in Game 5 of baseball's American League Division Series, Wednesday, Oct. 14, 2015 in Toronto. (Frank Gunn/The Canadian Press via AP) MANDATORY CREDIT Nathan Denette Rangers take lead on bizarre play in Game 5 of ALDS 
Texas Rangers' Rougned Odor, left, celebrates with Prince Fielder after scoring a run during the seventh inning in Game 5 of baseball's American League Division Series against the Toronto Blue Jays, Wednesday, Oct. 14, 2015 in Toronto. (Nathan Denette/The Canadian Press via AP) MANDATORY CREDIT Nathan Denette Rangers take lead on bizarre play in Game 5 of ALDS 
A grounds crew member collects beer cans thrown on to the field after the Texas Rangers scored a run during the seventh inning in Game 5 of baseball's American League Division Series, Wednesday, Oct. 14, 2015 in Toronto. (Nathan Denette/The Canadian Press via AP) MANDATORY CREDIT Posted: Wednesday, October 14, 2015 3:48 pm Rangers take lead on bizarre play in Game 5 of ALDS Associated Press | 
TORONTO (AP) â€” A deflected throw back to the mound by Toronto catcher Russell Martin allowed Texas to score the tiebreaking run in the seventh inning, touching off a long delay and causing the Blue Jays to play Game 5 of the AL Division Series under protest. 
Fans littered the field with debris during the 18-minute delay as umpires sorted out one of the most unusual plays in playoff history. Subscription Required An online service is needed to view this article in its entirety. You
